===Etymology===
From Late {{inh|en|enm|abaishen}}, {{m|enm|abaisse}}, {{m|enm|abassen}}, {{m|enm|abesse}}, {{m|enm|abessen||to be upset; to embarrass; to surprise; to confound; to bend down, stoop; to abase, degrade, disgrace}}, from {{der|en|frm|abaisser}}, from {{der|en|fro|abaissier}}, {{m|fro|abessier||to prostrate oneself; to lower, reduce}} (also compare {{cog|fro|esbahir||to amaze}}, {{cog|VL.|abbassiāre||to lower}}),<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=abaishen, v.|id=MED22|accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref> from {{m|fro|a-||''prefix indicating movement towards something''}} (from {{der|en|la|ad||toward, to}}, ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₂éd||at, to}}) + {{m|fro|baissier||to lower}} (from {{der|en|ML.|bassus||short of stature, low; base}}, possibly from {{der|en|grc|βᾰ́σῐς||foot; base, foundation}}, ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*gʷem-||to step}}).<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=2}}</ref><ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=2}}</ref> The spelling of the English word has been influenced by {{m|en|base}}.<ref>{{R:Oxford Dictionaries Online}}</ref>

